body:
When compiling this code, which misses `T: SomeTrait` bounds in the impls, the missing bounds are reported for the struct, which does already have that bound:

[playground](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=nightly&mode=debug&edition=2018&gist=b2da3793b310639f5441d317c9302626)
```rust
trait SomeTrait {
    type SomeAssociatedType: Copy;
}

// Reported error location is in the line below
struct SomeStruct<T: SomeTrait>(T::SomeAssociatedType);

// The actual errors are missing T: SomeTrait bounds below
impl<T> Copy for SomeStruct<T> {}

impl<T> Clone for SomeStruct<T> {
    fn clone(&self) -> Self {
        *self
    }
}
```

The error message is especially confusing as it suggests adding an already existing bound and offers no help in locating the actual issue:
```
error[E0277]: the trait bound `T: SomeTrait` is not satisfied
 --> src/lib.rs:5:33
  |
5 | struct SomeStruct<T: SomeTrait>(T::SomeAssociatedType);
  |                                 ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ the trait `SomeTrait` is not implemented for `T`
  |
  = help: consider adding a `where T: SomeTrait` bound
```

When implementing an empty trait instead of `Copy` and `Clone` the error is reported for the correct location.

This is manually reduced as much as I could. In a larger code base it is much harder to figure out the location of the missing trait bound.

I tested on playground with stable/nightly and 2015/2018 as well as locally with
```
rustc 1.32.0-nightly (13c943992 2018-11-18)
binary: rustc
commit-hash: 13c9439925797cd7a65c917d047c07a500d9bfe6
commit-date: 2018-11-18
host: x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu
release: 1.32.0-nightly
LLVM version: 8.0
```
